aws::graph::propositions: # Piper PA 18-150 Aircraft Accident Information
The accident involved structural icing as the defining event.
The accident included a collision with terrain/object (non-CFIT).
The pilot held a Commercial certificate.
The pilot was 42 years old.
The pilot held a Single-engine land airplane rating.
The pilot occupied the front seat.
The pilot had no other aircraft ratings.
The pilot used a 4-point restraint.
The pilot held an Instrument Rating for Airplane.
No second pilot was present during the accident.
The pilot had no instructor ratings.
No toxicology was performed on the pilot.
The pilot held a Class 3 Medical Certification without waivers/limitations.
The pilot's last FAA Medical Exam was on November 3, 2010.
The pilot was not an occupational pilot.
The pilot's last Flight Review or Equivalent was on August 1, 2011.
The pilot had 4800 hours of total flight time across all aircraft.
The pilot had 4500 hours of flight time in this make and model.
The aircraft was manufactured by Piper.
The aircraft registration was N40579.
The aircraft model was PA 18-150 A150.
The aircraft category was Airplane.
The aircraft was manufactured in 1976.
The aircraft had a Normal airworthiness certificate.
The aircraft serial number was 18-7509129.
The aircraft had a tailwheel landing gear type.
The aircraft's last inspection was an Annual inspection on March 10, 2013.
The aircraft's certified maximum gross weight was 1750 lbs.
The aircraft had flown 210 hours since the last inspection.
The aircraft had one reciprocating engine.
The aircraft had 5991 total airframe hours at the time of the accident.
The engine was manufactured by LYCOMING.
The engine model was O-320 SERIES.
The engine was rated at 160 Horsepower.
The aircraft owner was on file.
The aircraft operator was on file.
The operator held no operating certificates.
